00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:25.680
we decided to retire AZ Tidy Tuesday. So this is something of the past.

00:23:27.199 --> 00:23:30.560
Now, let me go back to this. Let me go back to the diversity of learning.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:38.959
AZ Tidy Tuesday fits on the top left. Because you can go back in time, all the codes,

00:23:38.959 --> 00:23:44.959
all the images, all the graphs are actually stored on a SharePoint online. So if you want

00:23:44.959 --> 00:23:50.560
to go back in time, you can go back to edition number one. And you can go back to the code of

00:23:51.119 --> 00:23:57.280
that given person for edition number one. And it's a mix of self-led learning index and

00:23:58.640 --> 00:24:06.079
also people walking you by the hand. Because we were doing some code review for every single

00:24:06.079 --> 00:24:11.760
entry for the first few editions of Tidy Tuesday. So that's why it's AZ Tidy Tuesday.

00:24:12.719 --> 00:24:18.640
But as I was saying, very early on, we were like, okay, maybe we could organize an internal

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:24.479
R conference. We knew it was going to be a big piece, but we also knew that it was going to be

00:24:24.479 --> 00:24:31.359
good for the community. And if we think about it, a conference is pretty much a synchronous

00:24:31.359 --> 00:24:37.359
kind of thing. Because if you miss it, you're going to be losing a lot of the interactivity.

00:24:37.359 --> 00:24:43.839
And then it's a mix between self-led and people taking you by the hand. But in a nutshell,

00:24:43.839 --> 00:24:49.199
it was a half-day event. We had 10 plus hours of content related to our 30 speakers,

00:24:50.239 --> 00:24:57.839
close to 30 posters, and all of these from close to 100 authors. And we were very fortunate to have

00:24:57.839 --> 00:25:05.119
Max Kuhn. So now from Posit, formerly known as RStudio. So that was pretty cool.

00:25:06.079 --> 00:25:11.920
And it was the first time we were doing this. So we didn't know how it was going to be received.

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:18.079
We didn't know if people were going to be showing up. We were blown away. And actually, the feedback

00:25:18.079 --> 00:25:26.479
was stellar. And we had more than 500 participants in this internal R conference. So seeing this,

00:25:26.479 --> 00:25:31.520
we're like, OK, we can't just stop here. We have to keep going. We have to keep

00:25:32.479 --> 00:25:38.959
promoting initiatives. We have to keep inventing initiatives. And that's what we did in 2022.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:47.199
And one of these initiatives is the R function of the month. So the concept is that we detail

00:25:47.199 --> 00:25:51.920
one R function. And by we, I actually mean Daniel here, because this is led by Daniel.

00:25:52.479 --> 00:25:59.439
And he does this in the form of a blog post. It happens once a month. And again, we leverage

00:25:59.439 --> 00:26:05.199
our internal social media. So on our internal social media, we do a workplace post, a Facebook

00:26:05.199 --> 00:26:12.319
post. And that's actually how it looks like. So it's an R markdown. It's a .html. And people can

00:26:12.319 --> 00:26:17.199
go back to it. There's a nice description. And for example, in this one, it was about

00:26:17.199 --> 00:26:23.760
pivot longer and pivot wider. And there is chunks of code so that people can basically

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:29.920
consult this and learn about this function, about this given package of their own later.

00:26:30.719 --> 00:26:37.119
So that's the R function of the month. And if we go back to this, then this is pretty much

00:26:37.119 --> 00:26:45.359
self-led, because you are going to have to make the effort to go through this .html. But you can

00:26:45.359 --> 00:26:49.839
pretty much go back in time, because it's very easy to consult this and to have a look at this.

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:57.199
Now, another initiative that we kicked off this year, and this is led by Gustav Satterstrom,

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:02.319
is something that we're calling the Learns and Learns. And the whole idea of the Learns and

00:27:02.319 --> 00:27:10.319
Learns is that we know that time is scarce. So we decided, OK, let's tackle one topic at a time,

00:27:10.319 --> 00:27:17.280
and let's have 30-minute sessions. So about a 20-minute presentation, 5-10 minutes Q&A.

00:27:18.319 --> 00:27:26.719
And same thing, happening once a month, and having inclusion in mind while alternating between the US

00:27:26.719 --> 00:27:33.439
and Europe. And we've got, so for these kind of events, we had a mix of internal speakers and

00:27:33.439 --> 00:27:40.400
external speakers. And, for example, in here, we had a presentation from Monika Huynh, who is one

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:46.000
of our collaborators, and she talked about Plotly. But some other people called about R Markdown,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:51.920
or some other people talked about many other topics, about packages that they had developed.

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:58.880
So that's the Learns and Learns. And again, the Learns and Learns are very much synchronous events,

00:27:58.880 --> 00:28:04.239
because if you miss this, it's going to be hard. You're going to be able to catch up,

00:28:04.239 --> 00:28:11.520
but you will, again, lose the interactivity. Now, let me move on to something that we brought

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:20.400
it as the 10-to-1s. So the 10-to-1s are led by Tom Marlow. And the idea with this was, OK,

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:26.640
we need to federate this community, and we want people to get to know each other.

00:28:27.520 --> 00:28:36.560
So let's ask to our users 10 questions. And each month is going to be the exact same 10 questions.

00:28:37.280 --> 00:28:43.760
And again, it's once a month. And in here, you can see the layout of the 10-to-1s.

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:50.880
So this was from a few months ago. And what I really like with this initiative is that you can

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:56.719
flip through the different 10-to-1s, like you would flip through a magazine. And you can see

00:28:56.719 --> 00:29:03.680
the diversity. And that's where you see that everyone learns differently. Everyone has

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:12.160
different kinds of tips on how to learn all. And if we look at this, the 10-to-1s, you can

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:16.560
pretty much go back in time, because you can be, OK, I'm going to be catching up on the 10 past

00:29:16.560 --> 00:29:23.680
editions. I'm going to be flipping through the magazine of the 10-to-1s. And I would say

00:29:24.479 --> 00:29:31.760
people are going to be taking you by the hand, because the tips are very precise. So it's a

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:37.839
gem, because you can very easily apply this to your day-to-day work.

00:29:40.319 --> 00:29:44.560
And initially, I was saying that we were leveraging our internal social media,

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:51.439
and that we were doing all our communications via our internal social media. And this was true

00:29:52.239 --> 00:29:58.160
until very recently. And again, it's a question of inclusion and diversity, because we know that

00:29:58.160 --> 00:30:05.839
not everyone is checking our internal social media. So we decided, OK, let's launch a monthly

00:30:05.839 --> 00:30:12.479
newsletter. And Shili Zhang is the one leading this. And the idea is a newsletter. So you've

00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:17.920
got all news, internal and external. It's one single email. We're not spamming you. And it's

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:24.239
happening once a month, by the middle of the month. And this is how it looks. And basically,

00:30:24.239 --> 00:30:32.959
Shili is collating everything that has happened in the past month, every single R and AZ initiative

00:30:32.959 --> 00:30:40.959
that has happened in the past month. And so what has been going on externally? Is there, let's say,

00:30:41.040 --> 00:30:47.839
on Pharma, is there a meetup coming up? These kind of things. So now let's go back to this.

00:30:49.359 --> 00:30:56.000
The newsletter pretty much fits in here. But that's not it, because we've got other kinds

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:02.560
of initiatives. And one of them, we are calling it, let's meet each other. And again, it goes back

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:07.359
to getting to know each other. Because I think at the end of the day, that's all that matters.

00:31:07.359 --> 00:31:12.560
We want, as human beings, we crave these connections. We want to know each other. We

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:18.800
want to build connections with other people. And then these connections are going to be helping

00:31:19.599 --> 00:31:24.319
building connections across departments. So that's what is let's meet each other.

00:31:24.319 --> 00:31:30.160
It's a very informal get together. It's a 30 minute session. You connect, you don't connect,

00:31:30.160 --> 00:31:36.319
doesn't matter. And you get to meet other R users in the organization. Sometimes we talk about R,

00:31:36.319 --> 00:31:40.560
sometimes we talk about other things. One thing we discussed, for example, was,

00:31:40.560 --> 00:31:44.880
how do you, what do you think about Posit, about the new name? What do you think about Posit?

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:49.599
Another time we talked about the holidays. Another time we talked about our favorite R package.

00:31:50.239 --> 00:31:59.920
So plenty of things. And then recently, we also did some workshops jointly with Posit.

00:32:00.479 --> 00:32:05.920
And we've done two so far. And we are very much looking forward to be doing more with Posit,

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:13.280
because they were very well received in the organization. And last but not least, the very,

00:32:14.239 --> 00:32:20.959
the latest initiative that we launched is something that we called the AZR Hot Desk.

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:27.760
And the whole idea in here is, you come with your question. It's a face to face kind of event.

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:34.800
You come with your question, and we're going to be helping you to answer this R related question.

00:32:35.920 --> 00:32:40.400
So that's what we're doing in the community of R users at AstraZeneca.

00:32:41.839 --> 00:32:48.959
Now, of course, all of these initiatives, and in total, we've got, in 2022, we had eight

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:55.439
initiatives going on at the same time. Now we've got seven, because tidy Tuesday,

00:32:55.439 --> 00:33:01.920
AZTidyTuesday retired. But I won't lie, it does take quite a substantial amount of time.

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:07.280
But behind the scenes, I'm the one doing the talking today, but behind the scenes,

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:15.839
there's a great team working fabulously. And they did an amazing job throughout the year.

00:33:15.839 --> 00:33:20.880
And I don't think we would be here today without that education, without their passion,

00:33:21.439 --> 00:33:24.719
and without their commitment. So I want to thank them.

00:33:25.439 --> 00:33:31.280
If you want to know more about the community, we've written a blog post, which is available

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:38.319
on the Puzzlet blog. So you can type this on your favorite browser, and you'll be able to find this.

00:33:38.880 --> 00:33:43.680
Otherwise, you can flash the QR code, and you will also land right there.

00:33:44.239 --> 00:33:49.760
So before we wrap up, we've got another question for you.

00:33:52.239 --> 00:33:55.760
What is more valuable for you at this moment in time?

00:33:56.560 --> 00:34:01.839
What is more valuable for you at this moment in time?

00:34:08.639 --> 00:34:15.840
And again, let's aim for 50.

00:34:15.919 --> 00:34:32.959
Okay, so I would say, you know, everyone wants to have the best of both worlds. So

00:34:33.520 --> 00:34:39.760
they want to have what Gabriel presented, and potentially a bit of community as well.

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:49.199
So I think, Gabriel, I've got a question for you. So we talked about what we did in 2022,

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:56.320
both in terms of trainings, and you talked about the importance of the diversity of learnings with

00:34:57.199 --> 00:35:04.959
education, experience and exposure. But what is on your wish list for 2023?

00:35:05.120 --> 00:35:13.600
Well, I think one of the important things is we can train lots of people on how to use R,

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:20.239
but then we need to make sure that people use the skill that they have acquired,

00:35:20.239 --> 00:35:28.800
use it or lose it. So how do we make sure that there are opportunities for them to do so?

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:36.000
How do we make sure that there are projects lined up once the skill has been acquired?

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:41.760
How do we make sure, actually, that the lots of the training that we develop is developed in

00:35:41.760 --> 00:35:48.239
response to the need of a particular group, a particular function, a particular set of

00:35:48.239 --> 00:35:52.959
individuals? So the request to come to us, like it has been for the development of

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:58.479
our training for the SAS programmers, we evaluate what the training needs is,

00:35:58.479 --> 00:36:03.600
and we develop an intervention that I'm not going to say guarantees, but where we have

00:36:04.239 --> 00:36:09.600
some metrics of success from the beginning. How are we going to embed the skill? What is it that

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:13.679
we are aiming to achieve through this training? And then we are obviously looking at the

00:36:13.679 --> 00:36:18.719
opportunity of strengthening our collaboration with POSIT. So we're actually been discussing

00:36:19.199 --> 00:36:26.000
to second someone from POSIT to AstraZeneca to better understand some of our learning needs

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:32.719
and developing some solutions. So we're really looking forward to this opportunity for 2023.

00:36:32.719 --> 00:36:41.600
But Guillaume, maybe I'm curious of asking you the same question. What is on your wish list for 2023?

00:36:41.919 --> 00:36:50.399
Well, thank you very much, Gabrielle. I think for me it's going to be the connections and I'm going

00:36:50.399 --> 00:36:57.360
to be making the parallel with the picture I showed at the beginning. I think we are in a very

00:36:57.360 --> 00:37:05.679
nice place at the moment because we've got more and more connections between SAS and R. That's

00:37:05.679 --> 00:37:09.600
one thing. And there's more and more connections between the various languages. It doesn't matter

00:37:10.159 --> 00:37:18.239
if it's SAS or R. So that's one thing. Now, the other thing I'm very much looking forward to in 2023

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:25.199
is all the connections that are going to be made through the various departments at AstraZeneca.

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:30.800
And we often talk about how do we evaluate a community and how hard it is to actually

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:38.239
evaluate a community. I think all these connections at the end of the day do help

00:37:38.239 --> 00:37:44.959
the business, do help the organization. Because if you know that your friend that you met at

00:37:44.959 --> 00:37:50.479
Let's Meet Each Other or that you met at any other kind of event is also working on developing,

00:37:50.479 --> 00:37:54.639
let's say, a Shiny app, but you've never done this, then you might be able to reach out to

00:37:54.639 --> 00:37:59.679
that person instead of learning it the hard way. So that's what I'm very much looking forward to

00:37:59.679 --> 00:38:07.040
in 2023. So it's these bridges, these connections between people and between departments.

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:11.679
So thank you very much, Rachel, for having us today.

00:38:13.199 --> 00:38:16.479
Indeed. And I see lots of questions, Rachel.

00:38:16.479 --> 00:38:22.479
Oh, I was muted. Thank you so much for joining us, Gabrielle and Guillaume. It's really amazing

00:38:22.479 --> 00:38:27.439
to hear about all the different ongoing initiatives at AstraZeneca and about this

00:38:27.439 --> 00:38:32.560
growing community, too. I see a lot of love for AstraZeneca in the chat and a few people from

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:40.639
your team on as well. There are so many great questions here. So I'd love to see if we can get

00:38:40.639 --> 00:38:47.360
to as many as possible. I think we might have like over 30 questions here, though. So we'll do our

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:55.679
best. But let me actually pull over a question from the YouTube chat right now. I was trying

00:38:55.679 --> 00:39:04.399
to star some of them as we were going. But one question from Jeremy was, AZ Team,

00:39:04.399 --> 00:39:08.560
is there a company-wide community for data science or is it only in research?

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:22.399
So I can take this one. I can talk about the R community. So one thing that I did not mention

00:39:22.399 --> 00:39:30.159
is that today I talked about the R community, but we actually have other communities. So there

00:39:30.159 --> 00:39:36.479
is, for example, an imaging community. There is, for example, a Python community. So the R community

00:39:36.479 --> 00:39:46.000
is not the only community at AstraZeneca. Now answering Jeremy's question, the community

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:54.479
is an AstraZeneca-wide community. So that's why it was and it is important for us to have these

00:39:54.479 --> 00:40:01.360
diverse sets of initiatives so that we try to meet the needs of everyone. And when you think about

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:07.520
it, it's actually not that easy because if you sit in R&D, if you sit in research and development,

00:40:08.080 --> 00:40:13.360
then when you think of a topic, intuitively, you're going to be thinking of a topic which is

00:40:13.439 --> 00:40:18.879
research and development-oriented. So I think you have to be proactive and you have to

00:40:18.879 --> 00:40:22.639
make conscious decisions so that you include everyone.

00:40:24.399 --> 00:40:30.159
I see on Slido there's a question that got a lot of upvotes. So I think people are really

00:40:30.159 --> 00:40:36.719
feeling seen in this question. How do people at AstraZeneca find balance between training

00:40:36.719 --> 00:40:42.159
versus doing their actual job? And how is AstraZeneca leadership supported and enabled this

00:40:42.159 --> 00:40:47.760
balance? I think it's an interesting question. Finding balance at the end of the year is what

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:52.800
everybody's looking for. But I think I have to say, you know, this is always a tricky question.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:59.280
But I definitely have to say that AstraZeneca leadership has been very supportive,

00:40:59.919 --> 00:41:06.719
particularly when it comes to specific programs that we have developed. We had buy-in from them

00:41:06.800 --> 00:41:11.760
from the beginning in helping us steer the development of some of these programs as well.

00:41:12.719 --> 00:41:21.040
We do try to raise awareness of line managers, of the importance of ring-fencing,

00:41:21.679 --> 00:41:27.600
time for learning, and especially encourage, now that we have all of these resources and

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:35.520
opportunity, people to think about how training can help them achieve goals in their individual

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:42.479
development plans. So we can improve that because we haven't necessarily found the perfect balance.

00:41:42.479 --> 00:41:46.560
But I have to say that there is support from leadership is there, and I think it's quite

00:41:46.560 --> 00:41:52.560
crucial to make sure that these training programs land and people have the chance of taking advantage

00:41:52.560 --> 00:42:01.520
of them. Thank you. And I just wanted to remind everybody real quickly that if you're looking for

00:42:01.520 --> 00:42:07.199
where everybody is asking these questions, we have a Slido link, and I just put the link on the

00:42:07.199 --> 00:42:11.199
screen, and we can share it again in the chat. But you can also upvote some of the other questions

00:42:11.199 --> 00:42:20.080
so that they come up to the top too. Another popular question I see was from Dan over on Slido.

00:42:20.719 --> 00:42:26.959
Was there any issue with regulators, FDA, EMA, when you switched to R from SAS?

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:41.679
I'm happy to give it a go to this one, and Gabri, feel free to complete if you want.

00:42:42.879 --> 00:42:50.879
So I think, so we've not made a complete switch to R. There are other companies in the industry that

00:42:51.840 --> 00:43:03.919
decided to make this leap. We've not made it yet for a variety of reasons. We've not made it yet,

00:43:03.919 --> 00:43:13.199
and I think whether we like it or not, and I'm not saying us as an industry, SAS is going to remain

00:43:13.199 --> 00:43:20.800
a key player in the years to come. And again, for a variety of reasons, because if we take,

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:27.199
it can be AstraZeneca, it can be any other pharma company. If you've got SAS macros,

00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:32.000
if you've got SAS programs that are developed, it's going to be taking quite a substantial amount

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:36.879
of time before you can actually transition to another kind of programming language. It can be

00:43:36.879 --> 00:43:42.800
R, it can be Julia, it doesn't matter. So we've not completely made that shift,

00:43:44.159 --> 00:43:50.719
and I think if we do decide to make that shift, it's going to take a bit of time. However,

00:43:50.719 --> 00:43:58.479
in our workforce, what we see is that there is more and more people using a wide variety of languages.

00:43:59.280 --> 00:44:05.840
Do you want to compliment, Gabriele? No, I think I very much agree with what you say, Guillaume. I

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:15.760
think there is a recognition anyway that regulators are now fully aware of R and the power of R, so

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:22.639
things will change in the future. And for the moment, as Guillaume said, we are doing some of

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:30.399
the, validate some of the work in R and getting people prepared for that switch,

00:44:30.399 --> 00:44:33.760
basically. And when it happens, you might be the first one to know.

00:44:36.719 --> 00:44:43.919
Thank you. Another question over on Slido is, a challenge I find is having enterprise tools for

00:44:43.919 --> 00:44:49.040
R available for people to use after learning or training. How have you dealt with this at

00:44:49.040 --> 00:45:00.639
AstraZeneca? So I think R, we have several platforms that are available to our data

00:45:00.639 --> 00:45:06.560
scientists and researchers. I mean, R is obviously one of the tools that can be easily installed

00:45:07.600 --> 00:45:13.120
from our software store, so anybody can install it. It's installed. We have an RStudio server.

00:45:13.679 --> 00:45:23.360
You know, we have computing resources where R is available. So depending on your preferred way of

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:32.560
work, I would say that you, and Guillaume, please disagree with me if I am wrong, but depending on

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:37.840
the way that you prefer to work, there should be a solution available for you and you should

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:44.320
definitely be able to have access to R through these various platforms that are available.

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:50.800
And in fact, what we try to do in some courses is already run the training

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:56.719
on such platforms so that then the transition is even seamless.

00:46:00.639 --> 00:46:06.399
I also would like to add, if anybody was curious if their team had access to those and just didn't

00:46:06.399 --> 00:46:11.760
know, because I know that's hard across huge organizations, feel free to reach out to me if

00:46:11.760 --> 00:46:18.399
you ever want me to connect you with your account team here at Posit, too. At some point, I'll put

00:46:18.399 --> 00:46:26.879
my LinkedIn in the chat, too. But a lot of claps in the chat for you and people saying, very inspiring

00:46:26.879 --> 00:46:33.120
talk. Thank you so much. I see Joshua has asked, thank you both, Guillaume and Gabriella, for this

