That's a good question. Guillaume, do you want to take it or do you want me to reflect on the

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:56.719
training side of things? You can, I can let you reflect on the training side of things

00:46:56.719 --> 00:47:04.080
and I can compliment you. So actually, it is true that by default, one would think

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:14.239
machine learning equals Python. And it's possibly very true that lots of our data scientists

00:47:15.760 --> 00:47:22.879
that are working in machine learning might have chosen Python. I can say that the first course

00:47:22.879 --> 00:47:28.479
that we offered in machine learning was machine learning in R through some of my former collaborators

00:47:28.479 --> 00:47:38.879
at the University of Cambridge. But Guillaume, maybe you have a different take.

00:47:40.159 --> 00:47:46.080
No, I agree with you and I'm going to be alluding, I can't remember who said that in pharma,

00:47:46.639 --> 00:47:52.399
but I think, you know, in 2022, I think what is important is that we've got a set of tools.

00:47:52.959 --> 00:47:57.199
We've got, historically in the industry, in the pharmaceutical industry, it's been SAS.

00:47:57.199 --> 00:48:03.760
So we've got SAS, we've got R, we've got Python. Some of us use Julia. I think depending on what

00:48:03.760 --> 00:48:10.000
you do and depending on the requirements from the regulatory authorities, then you've got this set

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:17.760
of tools and you can tap on one tool or the other. And I don't think, and I think that's actually

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:22.639
quite important, I don't think we should limit ourselves to one programming language because

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:29.439
one programming language is going to be having some strength that the other doesn't have.

00:48:30.639 --> 00:48:38.239
And again, I think it goes back to personal preference. Some of us like better doing

00:48:38.239 --> 00:48:42.639
machine learning with R and some of us like better doing machine learning with Python.

00:48:42.639 --> 00:48:48.479
Depends to what you're the most comfortable with. As long as you get the job done.

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:59.199
Thank you. I see a few questions that touch upon a similar idea, but one was,

00:48:59.199 --> 00:49:05.760
would the AstraZeneca's Data Science Academy be available to the public to gain the expertise?

00:49:06.479 --> 00:49:11.120
And maybe I'll also ask, are there any other community resources you recommend too?

00:49:12.800 --> 00:49:23.520
In the current plans that we currently have, the resource itself is it's only an in-house

00:49:23.520 --> 00:49:33.120
resource. What I can say though is I am actually working on some training activity,

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:40.479
more in the format of summer schools or winter schools, where we can actually bring together

00:49:41.439 --> 00:49:50.239
academics and colleagues from AstraZeneca. I think that is what I personally, as a training

00:49:50.239 --> 00:49:58.239
organiser, I miss very much in organising events that are virtual, the lack of that networking

00:49:58.239 --> 00:50:03.760
component. So I'm currently working on a summer school for next year to take place in Cambridge

00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:11.600
that will be open to academic and member of the private sector. So opportunities like that,

00:50:11.600 --> 00:50:17.199
I'm really looking forward to open more up in the future. And as you know, sort of similar,

00:50:17.199 --> 00:50:23.040
the same spirit, some of our community activities, we also invite external speakers. We really try

00:50:23.600 --> 00:50:31.919
to increase the flow between our knowledge and networking opportunity between our

00:50:34.639 --> 00:50:38.879
academia and industry. Let's not forget that there are many other programmes that we did

00:50:38.879 --> 00:50:43.760
not talk about today. We have PhD programmes, we have internship programmes. So there are

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:51.520
other opportunities where we can create collaborations. So I would say probably stay

00:50:51.600 --> 00:50:54.800
tuned for the first AZ summer school.

00:50:59.840 --> 00:51:06.719
Love it. That's awesome. Okay, let me see. Going through some of the Slido questions,

00:51:06.719 --> 00:51:13.199
somebody else asked, how do you determine which people go through POSIT academy versus

00:51:13.199 --> 00:51:16.399
in-house training? Our team is exploring academy now.

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:22.719
So I think actually it's an interesting question. So we were actually some of the beta testers

00:51:23.439 --> 00:51:30.639
of POSIT academy. So we were one of the first to take advantage of the programme. And I think,

00:51:30.639 --> 00:51:36.159
you know, I don't know how much the people online know about POSIT academy, but I think

00:51:36.719 --> 00:51:42.320
one of the strengths of this programme is that the training, it's development built around a

00:51:42.879 --> 00:51:49.199
particular project or a particular objective. So the individuals that kind of applied to attend

00:51:49.199 --> 00:51:57.679
that course and needed to also propose a project that they would work on and around which the

00:51:57.679 --> 00:52:04.159
training was crafted. So I think we went on selecting individuals that had also quite a

00:52:04.159 --> 00:52:11.120
timely need to learn hard. They had the need to implement the skill. We try to also

00:52:12.719 --> 00:52:18.800
guarantee sort of an equal representation of participants from our different research areas.

00:52:19.760 --> 00:52:26.159
So that was kind of the approach that we used. So we actually do not normally do selection for

00:52:26.159 --> 00:52:30.879
participate on the courses where in this case is we did so that we wanted to get, you know,

00:52:31.199 --> 00:52:37.679
the most motivated individual with the most pressing need to acquire the skill

00:52:37.679 --> 00:52:48.000
and with the project line up to apply this to. So I would say selection was quite key in this case,

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:54.080
and we would continue to run this collaboration in this spirit of selecting participants that

00:52:54.080 --> 00:53:03.760
would mostly benefit. Thank you. Is it okay if I keep firing away a few more questions at you?

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:10.800
Okay. So going by some of the most upvoted questions here on Slido, one was how do you

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:17.280
do risk analysis for any tasks you are doing first time in R and submission studies?

00:53:17.280 --> 00:53:29.600
This one is yours, Guillaume. Thank you. Moral support all the way.

00:53:33.600 --> 00:53:39.040
So to the best of my knowledge, so as I was saying, we've not made the transition

00:53:39.919 --> 00:53:46.879
to R at the moment. And to the best of my knowledge, I'm not sure we've actually done

00:53:46.879 --> 00:53:55.199
any kind of submission using R. So I don't think I'm actually able to answer this question.

00:53:57.760 --> 00:54:03.360
I'm throwing all the hard questions at you right now. So the next most upvoted here was

00:54:05.439 --> 00:54:09.600
if SAS wouldn't have raised the prices by such a high percentage,

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:12.719
do you think open source would be less prevalent in pharma?

00:54:13.600 --> 00:54:19.760
So I can give it a go and Gab, we can complement as well if you want.

00:54:22.719 --> 00:54:29.760
I think there's a few things in this question. So there's definitely the

00:54:30.879 --> 00:54:38.719
price of the license that is definitely pricey. And for some organizations, it is an issue.

00:54:39.520 --> 00:54:43.600
And it has a huge impact on our budget as well. So that's one thing.

00:54:45.679 --> 00:54:52.000
But I think there's another aspect to it, which is the open source aspect.

00:54:53.679 --> 00:55:02.080
And as of today, when you want to consult, when you're reading a paper, and when you want to

00:55:02.399 --> 00:55:07.919
give a try to the statistical methodology or the new machine learning methodology,

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:15.520
it's going to be in the form of an R package. Some kind of development, some kind of open

00:55:15.520 --> 00:55:22.320
source development. And I think that's a big difference between SAS and R in the sense that

00:55:23.439 --> 00:55:29.360
there's all the regulatory work. And still, as of today, at AstraZeneca, it is SAS.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:34.719
But then there's all the question about exploratory and all the question about

00:55:34.719 --> 00:55:38.959
study design, if we take the example of designing randomized control trials.

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:48.000
And then that's where I think the strength of open source plays a big role. So I think even

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:54.719
if SAS would not have raised the prices that much, I still think open source would have played

00:55:54.719 --> 00:56:02.159
a key role in the pharmaceutical industry. And I think this is also, I think it's also linked to

00:56:02.159 --> 00:56:06.560
one of the questions that popped up, I think, on the YouTube channel. You know, Konstantinos was

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:12.560
asking, what are the dangers of using R or open source languages compared to licensed languages?

00:56:13.120 --> 00:56:22.639
And I wouldn't call it a danger, you know, but I'd say that when I first heard about R,

00:56:22.639 --> 00:56:31.520
you know, I, in my PhD, used closed tools. I didn't use R for any kind of analytical work

00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:35.120
that I did during my PhD. It gives you an idea of my age. Let's forget about that.

00:56:35.679 --> 00:56:42.560
But I think the advantage of open source is that you have a community. You have the experts

00:56:42.560 --> 00:56:49.280
in a field developing a solution that is available to you a few months after it has

00:56:49.280 --> 00:56:55.360
been developed. It's out there. You can use it. You can modify it. And it is not the same

00:56:55.360 --> 00:57:01.840
in environments like SAS, like MATLAB. We don't want to pick on SAS particularly. I think you

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:06.639
have that cutting edge, you have that community, you have that support. You post the question on

00:57:06.639 --> 00:57:11.840
the R community and, you know, the person that has developed the package answer you. It doesn't

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:18.479
get better than that in terms of access to expertise and knowledge. So I'm not going to

00:57:18.479 --> 00:57:23.360
say that we all have to ditch non-open source tools, but I think it's a great complement

00:57:23.919 --> 00:57:31.520
to be able to have that support and be able to move at quite a fast pace with open source.

00:57:34.959 --> 00:57:41.199
Thank you both. Okay. Is it okay? I know we scheduled maybe 15 minutes

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:45.520
extra to run over. Do you have to run to a meeting?

00:57:45.919 --> 00:57:50.479
No, that's okay for me. Yeah. Okay. There's so many great questions.

00:57:52.239 --> 00:57:57.280
Okay. So one of the first questions actually that came over on YouTube, and you might need

00:57:57.280 --> 00:58:03.919
to help me with some of the acronyms here. Does AZ use R or Python in a GMP environment,

00:58:03.919 --> 00:58:06.239
or is it just in research business functions?

00:58:07.120 --> 00:58:12.080
So, Gabri, do you have a good overview of all the platforms that we use?

00:58:13.360 --> 00:58:18.320
I'd probably say not an overview of all the platforms that we use.

00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:30.320
So I have been working with, so I can give it a try if you want. So I've been in contact with

00:58:30.479 --> 00:58:38.719
someone in late phase clinical trials, so late phase programming in randomized control trials.

00:58:40.479 --> 00:58:50.000
And this is definitely a hot topic, because if we want to push the use of R further at AstraZeneca,

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:56.560
there is definitely all the piece related to the training, how do we upskill our collaborators,

00:58:56.560 --> 00:59:02.560
but there is also all the piece regarding GXP compliant environments. So this is something

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:08.639
we're working on, and hopefully in the next few months, we should have an answer to this.

00:59:12.239 --> 00:59:18.959
Thank you. Going back and touching on the training aspects, somebody had asked,

00:59:18.959 --> 00:59:24.560
what KPIs does your team use to evaluate how much each course, or how much each course

00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:31.439
was? And Rachel, you said we only have 15 minutes.

00:59:34.639 --> 00:59:38.639
No, I mean, I briefly, briefly, briefly touched it when we were looking at those

00:59:39.760 --> 00:59:45.360
numbers for our R training, but this is actually something that I am quite passionate about.

00:59:45.360 --> 00:59:52.399
Even before joining AZ, I was already looking at how to measure quality and impact of short courses

00:59:53.120 --> 00:59:59.120
in one of the previous projects that I was involved in, which was actually a pan-European

01:00:00.959 --> 01:00:05.120
infrastructure, Elixir. And, you know, I think the way we approach it is,

01:00:05.919 --> 01:00:10.080
right after the course, we would measure the quality. Did you like the course? Do you think

01:00:10.080 --> 01:00:16.639
it was balanced? Are you planning to use the tools in your future work? What did you like the most?

01:00:16.639 --> 01:00:20.159
What did you like the least? You know, just to get a sense of how the course is received.

01:00:20.719 --> 01:00:27.360
And then, at intervals of six months after the course, well, six months after the course,

01:00:27.360 --> 01:00:31.840
we will circulate another survey where we are instead going to ask, are you using the tools?

01:00:34.159 --> 01:00:37.520
In what way has the training helped you? And you saw some of the

01:00:39.360 --> 01:00:43.520
questions that we asked, has it improved the way you code? Has it improved the way you collaborate?

01:00:44.159 --> 01:00:48.320
But we also ask questions around, have you actually passed your knowledge to others?

01:00:48.399 --> 01:00:56.159
Have you trained others on how to use the tools? So, we do collect some metrics, a combination of

01:00:56.159 --> 01:01:02.320
quantitative and qualitative, although these type of KPIs are often more qualitative than

01:01:02.320 --> 01:01:09.280
quantitative. We try to do some quantitation, but it's not perfect. But also, we do interviews,

01:01:10.560 --> 01:01:15.840
a round of interviews with our learners, just ask them, you know, some people,

01:01:16.479 --> 01:01:21.520
that by survey is definitely something that we are experiencing. So, it's nice to do some

01:01:21.520 --> 01:01:26.560
case studies. We have, you know, evidence of individuals that have changed roles,

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:32.159
and were not in a data science role, and then they are transitioning to one. We have several

01:01:32.159 --> 01:01:43.120
success stories on how the training is helping. So, we have a few sets of KPIs, but in some cases,

01:01:43.120 --> 01:01:47.919
it's also just, you know, interviews, and talking to the learners, and see how they've been

01:01:48.800 --> 01:01:58.959
affected. Great, thank you. Okay, we'll take maybe five more questions, if we can get through them,

01:01:58.959 --> 01:02:04.159
but I'll send you all the other questions too, and can try and group them together as well.

01:02:05.120 --> 01:02:11.679
But on Slido, I'm seeing right now the most upvoted is, how did you pick use cases that

01:02:11.679 --> 01:02:16.879
would motivate people to want to learn? Did you start with specific technologies to highlight the

01:02:16.879 --> 01:02:25.919
power of open source data science, like Shiny? I think when it comes to use cases,

01:02:27.360 --> 01:02:35.840
I think this is a bit of a, well, I would say that the success of the training program is also

01:02:36.479 --> 01:02:42.479
try to marry, you know, what is the need with what is the availability of the people that are

01:02:42.479 --> 01:02:47.439
going to contribute to the training program. Let me explain. When we work on use cases, you know,

01:02:47.439 --> 01:02:54.560
we try to showcase the work that others within the organization are doing. So, we want to kind of

01:02:54.560 --> 01:03:01.679
kill two birds with one stone. One is to already display how we are using data science,

01:03:01.679 --> 01:03:10.719
how we are utilizing one particular technology, and how is that enabling us to achieve

01:03:10.719 --> 01:03:16.320
particular goals in a way that you get also to inspire others. And that is where you go back to

01:03:16.320 --> 01:03:20.479
that peer-to-peer learning as well, how others are using the skill within the organization might be

01:03:20.479 --> 01:03:25.600
relevant for what I'm trying to do. But at the same time, it's also an opportunity for our subject

01:03:25.600 --> 01:03:30.800
matter experts, many of which contribute to our training, to showcase also what they do.

01:03:30.800 --> 01:03:37.439
So, give them that visibility. Make people aware of who are the experts within the organization.

01:03:37.439 --> 01:03:42.159
So, if I have a problem and I want to talk about the natural language process, who do I go and talk

01:03:42.159 --> 01:03:48.959
to? So, I think, you know, the selection of the use cases is what is that we think is up and

01:03:48.959 --> 01:03:55.280
coming and is going to be a hot topic of interest, but also where are our experts and how can we give

01:03:55.280 --> 01:04:00.879
them some visibility through showcasing some of their use case, of the work that they do through

01:04:00.879 --> 01:04:12.560
these use cases. Thank you. Okay, let's see. Trying to make sure I got to all the ones that

01:04:12.560 --> 01:04:17.600
uploaded up there. The other one on the training was, how much is the reproducible

01:04:17.600 --> 01:04:21.600
environments and workflows taught for all users going through the training?

01:04:25.280 --> 01:04:32.320
Well, I can definitely say that reproducible science, you know, is very high on our list.

01:04:32.320 --> 01:04:39.280
We can do better. We are developing more courses that are around the software best practices and

01:04:39.280 --> 01:04:46.000
how you work reproducibly. As I said before, we try to get more of our courses run of our

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:52.639
infrastructure. So, when the training is over, the infrastructure is already readily available

01:04:52.639 --> 01:05:00.320
to the user to continue their work. We have recently done a seminar, actually just last week,

01:05:00.320 --> 01:05:10.320
wasn't it, Guillaume, around the workflows in collaboration with POSIT. So, again, I think

01:05:10.320 --> 01:05:20.479
we definitely need to expose more of these and get more people to utilize our environments

01:05:20.479 --> 01:05:26.479
and adopt best practices. So, it is definitely something on the rise. How do you, you know,

01:05:26.479 --> 01:05:34.000
containers and reproducibility and portability is definitely something that is high on my list

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:45.760
for next year. Budget permitting. At the end of the year, Gabriele. I can add my Santa wish list,

01:05:45.760 --> 01:05:54.719
no? Absolutely. On the community front, I know, Guillaume, at R&Pharma, we were talking a bit about

01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:59.840
making things sustainable. And actually, somebody had asked, can you talk about why

01:06:00.399 --> 01:06:09.840
you decided to drop AZTidyTuesday? That's a very good question. It was not an easy decision

01:06:09.840 --> 01:06:17.679
because it was the first initiative we started and that's what built quite some momentum

01:06:17.679 --> 01:06:23.199
around the community. So, that was definitely not an easy decision. But the reason why we decided

01:06:23.199 --> 01:06:30.560
to drop AZTidyTuesday was basically we could see a drop in participation. So, that was one thing.

01:06:31.760 --> 01:06:38.959
And it was also the fact that, you know, all these initiatives, even if you think that at first they

01:06:38.959 --> 01:06:46.159
don't take time, they still do take some time. Because, you know, for every single AZTidyTuesday

01:06:46.159 --> 01:06:51.919
edition, we had to look for a dataset. So, it was a publicly available dataset. But we still had to

01:06:51.919 --> 01:06:59.600
look for one. And we had to frame it around a nice story. Then you have to select a featured entry.

01:06:59.600 --> 01:07:06.560
Then you have, you go through the codes. Then you select, we were selecting three to five nice

01:07:06.560 --> 01:07:12.080
things in the code that we were actually putting up so that everyone could benefit. So, you know,

01:07:12.080 --> 01:07:18.080
it was a matter of time, basically. And it was to create a bit of space,

01:07:18.080 --> 01:07:21.840
a bit of, yeah, a bit of space, a bit of time for new initiatives.

01:07:24.719 --> 01:07:32.000
Thank you. Okay. Two more questions, I promise. One great question over on Slido is,

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:37.919
are there teams in AZ that include both R-only people and SAS-only people?

01:07:37.919 --> 01:07:40.479
If yes, how did you manage them working together?

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:54.639
I think I can give a go to this one. I think this is kind of fading away, I would say. Because

01:07:55.199 --> 01:08:02.000
I was saying, you know, everyone is becoming multilingual these days. And I think it is true.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:07.679
And it is true for the new joiners in the industry. Because even if they learned R, Python,

01:08:07.679 --> 01:08:14.000
or Julia at university, when they join AstraZeneca as early career professionals,

01:08:15.520 --> 01:08:22.640
they have some SAS training. So, they become multilingual in SAS. Now, if we take the example

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:30.240
of people who have been with us for a longer period of time, and who are more versatile at

01:08:30.240 --> 01:08:37.919
SAS, I think they're also seeing the R journey, not only at AstraZeneca, but in the pharmaceutical

01:08:37.919 --> 01:08:44.720
industry. And if people want to remain competitive, they need to learn to use R.

01:08:44.720 --> 01:08:49.680
So, this kind of, you know, dichotomy between R-only people or SAS-only people, I don't think

01:08:49.680 --> 01:08:54.959
it exists anymore. And I don't think in the years to come, it's going to exist. Because

01:08:54.959 --> 01:09:00.560
everyone is multilingual, and everyone is going to be able to help each other out.

01:09:07.200 --> 01:09:13.200
Okay. So, in thinking about all the different community initiatives, I see Eric had a great

01:09:13.200 --> 01:09:18.879
question. How do you motivate community members to share their insights and learnings in the

01:09:18.879 --> 01:09:31.040
meetups or other sessions? That's a great one. And it very much relates to what we talked about

01:09:31.040 --> 01:09:37.759
in the past, Rachel. When we're like, I think what is important in communities is how do you

01:09:37.759 --> 01:09:45.040
make sure that your community goes from a receiving mode to a contributing mode?

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:55.120
And I was just looking earlier today at our Facebook equivalent group at AstraZeneca. And I

01:09:55.120 --> 01:10:00.160
was actually quite happy when I was scrolling through the feed of the group, because I was like,

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:05.759
I could see questions popping up and posts popping up. So, not many posts, you know, today,

01:10:05.759 --> 01:10:13.520
but like, you know, from the past few days. And these posts were not driven by steering committee

01:10:13.839 --> 01:10:20.959
members. And I think that's the hardest bit, maybe. How do you make sure that you create,

01:10:20.959 --> 01:10:24.399
we talked about this as well in the past, how do you make sure you create a safe space

01:10:25.200 --> 01:10:33.040
so that everyone is fine being vulnerable in such an environment and being like, okay,

01:10:33.040 --> 01:10:38.240
I'm going to be asking a question. Maybe it's a simple question, but it doesn't matter.

01:10:38.959 --> 01:10:48.240
And I think that's kind of how we motivate others. We try to create this safe space so that

01:10:48.240 --> 01:10:56.000
everyone can speak up. That's one thing. And the other thing is, we've got different kinds of

01:10:56.000 --> 01:11:07.120
initiatives. Some of them require quite a level of awe, but some of them, let's say the Lunch and

01:11:07.120 --> 01:11:15.279
Learns, we make sure that we don't overcomplicate things so that it's also open for a beginner to

01:11:15.279 --> 01:11:21.359
present in a few editions. And very much like what you say, Rachel, when you talk about, you know,

01:11:21.359 --> 01:11:28.560
the journey of a participant, maybe that person is going to be joining the media first, not speaking,

01:11:28.560 --> 01:11:32.959
then following that person is going to be asking a question. And then the goal is to have that

01:11:32.959 --> 01:11:39.040
person present something at some point. So that's what we try to do.

01:11:41.279 --> 01:11:46.080
And I would say that there is a lot of enthusiasm, though, within the organisation for sharing.

01:11:46.720 --> 01:11:56.879
So when I was, for some reason, part of one of the sponsors of our community conference,

01:11:57.600 --> 01:12:04.240
and I think there was a lot of uptake. People really volunteered to participate, present,

01:12:04.799 --> 01:12:09.919
co-organise. I think one thing that we have to appreciate, and I didn't when I joined the

01:12:09.919 --> 01:12:15.919
organisation, this is a very vast organisation. So you can be an R user, you know, relatively

01:12:15.919 --> 01:12:21.200
isolated in your group, trying to do something, not knowing what others are doing. So I think

01:12:21.200 --> 01:12:28.479
establishing these networks and meetings or meetups, people really value the fact that they

01:12:28.479 --> 01:12:34.959
can share experience and connect. So I think the enthusiasm is definitely there. I don't think we

01:12:34.959 --> 01:12:40.879
need to do too much motivation. That's a great point, though, Gabrielle. Sometimes people might

01:12:40.879 --> 01:12:46.720
be working in a team where they don't know about the community that exists already. And

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:53.759
if in the future, somebody is watching this meetup recording on YouTube, and they're from

01:12:53.759 --> 01:12:59.279
AstraZeneca, and they just started, how do they go about finding out about the community events?

01:13:02.319 --> 01:13:07.279
As Guillaume said, you know, we have social media, everybody's added to that social media.

01:13:08.479 --> 01:13:14.160
You know, we are, I'm personally working on getting more data science learning onto onboarding.

01:13:14.799 --> 01:13:20.560
So, you know, it's all about raising awareness of what's out there and what's available.

01:13:20.560 --> 01:13:28.479
So I think there are channels for newcomers to do so, but I'm sure we can improve in that respect

01:13:28.479 --> 01:13:35.359
as well. But there are various channels through which they can become aware.

01:13:36.319 --> 01:13:43.680
Great. Thank you both so much, Gabrielle and Guillaume. It's really been great getting to

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:48.640
to join some of the R and Pharma events and to get to meet you both and work with you both.

01:13:49.200 --> 01:13:54.640
It's so impressive to see all the training and community building that that you both do.

01:13:54.640 --> 01:13:57.680
Thank you very much. Thank you for the invite.

01:13:58.640 --> 01:14:01.359
You're welcome. With the pleasure. Thank you.

01:14:01.359 --> 01:14:06.319
For for others listening in, I also wanted to just give you a heads up,

01:14:06.319 --> 01:14:11.839
and I just put it into the chat too. But it's a big Pharma week for us here,

01:14:11.839 --> 01:14:17.759
because we also have Christina Fillmore, a data science leader at GSK joining us as a featured

01:14:17.759 --> 01:14:24.479
leader at the data science hangout this Thursday as well. So I also just put that into the chat.

01:14:25.120 --> 01:14:29.040
But I want to thank you all for all your great questions and for being here

01:14:29.040 --> 01:14:35.439
and joining us today as well. Have a great rest of the day, everybody. Thank you so much.

